# Rust Code Quality — CDK

## No redundant comments
Only explain *why*, never *what*. Delete comments that restate the code.
```rust
// ❌  Increment the counter
*t = t.wrapping_add(1);

// ✅  wrapping_add avoids UB on tick counter overflow
*t = t.wrapping_add(1);
```

## Errors must be handled
Never silently discard a `Result` or `Option`.  
Use `ok_or(...)`, `unwrap_or_else(...)`, or propagate with `?`.
```rust
// ❌
let _ = queue.push(task);

// ✅
if queue.push(task).is_err() {
    crate::println!("scheduler: queue full, task dropped");
}
```

## Unsafe blocks need a SAFETY comment
Every `unsafe` block must have a `// SAFETY:` comment explaining the invariant.
```rust
// ✅
// SAFETY: identity-mapped — phys == virt; frame is 4 KiB aligned.
unsafe { &mut *(phys as *mut X86PageTable) }
```

## Tests are required for new public logic
Every new public function with non-trivial behaviour needs at least one test.  
Tests live in `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` at the bottom of the same file.  
Use the `cargo test-host` alias (`cargo test --target aarch64-apple-darwin --lib`).

## Static globals use spin::Mutex
Mutable shared kernel state goes in `static FOO: Mutex<T>`.  
Use `try_lock()` inside interrupt handlers — never `lock()`.
